Meaning:
to receive.
e.g. He accepts defeat well.

to take or leave out.
e.g. Please take all the books off the shelf except for the red one.

to influence.
e.g. Lack of sleep affects the quality of your work.

noun, result.
e.g. The subtle effect of the lighting made the room look ominous.
verb, to accomplish.
e.g. Can the university effect such a change without disrupting classes?

an indirect reference.
e.g. The professor made an allusion to Virginia Woolf's work.

a false perception of reality.
e.g. They saw a mirage: that is a type of illusion one sees in the desert.

prepared.
e.g. Dinner was all ready when the guests arrived.

by this time.
e.g. The turkey was already burned when the guests arrived.

entirely.
e.g. Altogether, I thought that the student's presentation was well planned.

gathered, with everything in one place.
e.g. We were all together at the family reunion last spring.

to be separated.
e.g. The chain-link fence kept the angry dogs apart.

to be joined with.
e.g. The new course was a part of the new field of study at the university.

climb.
e.g. The plane's ascent made my ears pop.

agreement.
e.g. The martian assented to undergo experiments.

noun, air inhaled or exhaled.
e.g. You could see his breath in the cold air.

verb, to inhale or exhale.
e.g. If you don't breathe, then you are dead.

seat of government. Also financial resources.
e.g. The capital of Virginia is Richmond.

the actual building in which the legislative body meets
e.g. The governor announced his resignation in a speech given at the capitol today.

to quote or document
e.g. I cited ten quotes from the same author in my paper.

vision
e.g. The sight of the American flag arouses different emotions in different parts of the world.

position or place
e.g. The new office building was built on the site of a cemetery.

noun, something that completes; verb, to complete
e.g. A nice dry white wine complements a seafood entree.

noun, praise; verb, to praise
e.g. The professor complimented Betty on her proper use of a comma.

sense of right and wrong
e.g. The student's conscience kept him from cheating on the exam.

awake
e.g. I was conscious when the burglar entered the house.

a group that consults or advises
e.g. The men and women on the council voted in favor of an outdoor concert in their town.

to advise
e.g. The parole officer counseled the convict before he was released.

to draw or bring out
e.g. The teacher elicited the correct response from the student.

illegal
e.g. The Columbian drug lord was arrested for his illicit activities.

famous, respected
e.g. The eminent podiatrist won the Physician of the Year award.

inherent or intrinsic
e.g. The meaning of the poem was immanent, and not easily recognized.

ready to take place
e.g. A fight between my sister and me is imminent from the moment I enter my house.

of or belonging to it
e.g. The baby will scream as soon as its mother walks out of the room.

contraction for it is
e.g. It's a beautiful day in the neighborhood.

noun, a type of metal
e.g. Is that pipe made of lead?

verb, past tense of the verb "to lead"
e.g. She led the campers on an over-night hike.

to lie down (a person or animal. hint: people can tell lies)
e.g. I have a headache, so I'm going to lie down for a while.

to lay an object down.
e.g. "Lay down that shotgun, Pappy!" The sheriff demanded of the crazed moonshiner.

verb, to misplace or not win
e.g. Mom glared at Mikey. "If you lose that new lunchbox, don't even think of coming home!"

adjective, to not be tight; verb (rarely used)--to release
e.g. The burglar's pants were so loose that he was sure to lose the race with the cop chasing him.

noun, a book that is a work of fiction. Do not use "novel" for nonfiction; use "book" or "work."
e.g. Mark Twain wrote his novel Adventures of Huckleberry Finn when he was already well known, but before he published many other works of fiction and nonfiction.

verb, past tense of "to pass," to have moved
e.g. The tornado passed through the city quickly, but it caused great damage.

belonging to a former time or place
e.g. Who was the past president of Microsquish Computers?

to come before
e.g. Pre-writing precedes the rough draft of good papers.

to go forward
e.g. He proceeded to pass back the failing grades on the exam.

adjective, most important; noun, a person who has authority
e.g. The principal ingredient in chocolate chip cookies is chocolate chips.

a general or fundamental truth
e.g. The study was based on the principle of gravity.

verb, to cite
e.g. I would like to quote Dickens in my next paper.

noun, the act of citing
e.g. The book of famous quotations inspired us all.

to hesitate or feel unwilling
e.g. We became reluctant to drive further and eventually turned back when the road became icy.

to be reluctant to speak; to be reserved in manner
e.g. They called him reticent, because he rarely spoke. But he listened carefully and only spoke when he had something important to say.

standing still
e.g. The accident was my fault because I ran into a stationary object.

writing paper
e.g. My mother bought me stationery that was on recycled paper.

correct form for "to be obligated to" or "presumed to"
e.g. We are supposed to check our bags before we board.

to guess or make a conjecture
e.g. Do you suppose we will get to the airport on time?

use with comparisons
e.g. I would rather go out to eat than eat at the dining hall.

at that time, or next
e.g. I studied for my exam for seven hours, and then I went to bed.

possessive form of they
e.g. Their house is at the end of the block.

indicates location
e.g. There goes my chance of winning the lottery!

contraction for "they are"
e.g. They're in Europe for the summer--again!

by means of; finished; into or out of
e.g. He plowed right through the other team's defensive line.

past tense of throw
e.g. She threw away his love letters.

careful or complete
e.g. John thoroughly cleaned his room; there was not even a speck of dust when he finished.

however; nevertheless
e.g. He's really a sweetheart though he looks tough on the outside.

abbreviated slang for through; not appropriate in standard writing
e.g. We're thru for the day!

toward
e.g. I went to the University of Richmond.

also, or excessively
e.g. He drank too many screwdrivers and was unable to drive home.

a number
e.g. Only two students did not turn in the assignment.

pronoun, referring to a person or persons
e.g. Jane wondered how Jack, who is so smart, could be having difficulties in Calculus.

pronoun, replacing a singular or plural thing(s);not used to refer to persons
e.g. Which section of history did you get into?

used to refer to things or a group or class of people
e.g. I lost the book that I bought last week.

used as an object
e.g. Whom did Sarah choose as her replacement?
